<br>
11 January 2003: The Agni-III missile that India will test-fire by the year-end is meant to &quot;dissuade&quot; China from launching a nuclear attack and not deter it as is the case of the Pakistan-specific Agni-I missile. <br>
<br>
Top officials made a distinction between the &quot;dissuasive posture&quot; that Agni-III is meant to represent and deterrence, the logic being that India cannot deter China from nuking India with its larger number of nuclear missiles but that Agni-III's capability to hit the heartland of China should dissuade it from launching a nuclear strike. <br>
<br>
Scientific advisor to the defence minister, V.K.Aatre, today disclosed the likely test of Agni-III with a range of plus-3,000 kilometres. <br>
<br>
India has already constituted a missile group for Prithvi and is raising another, while Agni-I, Agni-II, and Agni-III missile groups would be raised within the 10th-Plan period, with priority being given to the Agni-I missile group, while the Agni-III missile group's constitution depends on the success of the missile test. <br>
<br>
A missile group could consist of anywhere between 400-500 men of which 100 men form core with a quarter of them designated as missile experts. <br>
<br>
The Prithvi missile group took five years to form but the Agni-I, Agni-II and Agni-III missile groups would be raised in a maximum of three years that includes training of the core group in the Defence Research and Development Organisation and other government research establishments, detailed familiarisation with weapon-systems, and close study of strategic issues. <br>
<br>
The existing and to-be-raised army missile groups will be gradually brought under the newly-formed strategic command alongwith air force strategic bomber squadrons and naval nuclear submarines, and the new strategic forces commander, Air Marshal T.M.Asthana, is tasked to integrate these various systems into one command. <br>
